Introduction: Data and Problem Summary

With the advance in machine learning techniques, an increasing number of jurisdictions across the United States are using risk assessment instruments (RAIs) to help judges make bail decisions. These statistical models are often used pre-trial to predict the likelihood that the defendent will commit a crime if released on bail pending their court date.

A major concern with the use of such models is that they might serve to exacerbate bias already present in the criminal justice system by exaggerating or otherwise distorting the meaning of patterns in the data used to train these statistical models. This risk is especially high when RAIs trained on the data of one jurisdiction are later applied to populations of defendents from a completely different jurisdiction. In the case that the new population possesses features not present in the population on which the RAI was trained, we would expect these differences to have a detrimental effect on the RAIs predictive accuracy.

This is the central concern that motivates the current investigation. For the past several years, courts in Broward County, Florida have been using one of the RAIs in the COMPAS suite to inform pretrial release decisions by predicting the likelihood that a particular defendent will recidivate. In May 2016, investigative journalists from the independents, non-profit newsroom ProPublica conducted an anlysis of one commerical RAI, the COMPAS tool by Northpointe (which stands for Correctional Offender Management Profiling for Alternative Sanctions), and found that black defendants were far more likely than white defendants to be incorrectly judged to be at a higher risk of recidivism, while white defendants were more likely than black defendants to be incorrectly flagged as low risk (https://www.propublica.org/article/how-we-analyzed-the-compas-recidivism-algorithm).

The ProPublica team analyzed the COMPAS scores for both Risk of Recidivism as well as Risk of Violent Recidivism. In this report, I will use the publicly released data from their analysis to attempt to reproduce these two analyses in order to provide independent evidence either in support or in refutation of their findings. An overview of the key tasks covered in this report as well as other supporting resources is provided on the course website at http://www.andrew.cmu.edu/user/achoulde/95791/lectures/lecture05/project_list.html.

About the Data

For this study, the ProPublica team looked at more than 10,000 criminal defendants in Broward County, Florida, and compared their predicted recidivism rates with the true rate measured over a two-year period (2013-2014). When the defendants are booked in jail, they are required to respond to a COMPAS questionnaire. Their answers are then fed into the COMPAS software to generate several scores, including predictions of Risk of Recidivism and Risk of Violent Recidivism. Because Broward County primarily uses these scores to determine whether to release or detain a defendant before his or her trial, the team discarded all scores that were assessed at parole, probation, or other stages in the criminal justice system, leaving them with 11,757 people who were assessed at the pretrial stage (https://www.propublica.org/article/how-we-analyzed-the-compas-recidivism-algorithm).

The team then supplemented this database of COMPAS scores with a profile of each individuals criminal history, both before and after they were scored. (This public criminal records data was collected from the Broward County Clerks Office website through April 1, 2016.) This data included approximately 80,000 criminal records in total. Records were matched using the defendents first and last names and date of birth, resulting in an estimated error rate of 3.75 percent (CI: +/- 1.8 percent). Race was assigned using the Broward County Sheriffs Offices race classification system, which identifies defendants as black, white, Hispanic, Asian and Native American. In 343 cases, the race was marked as Other. Finally, the team compiled each persons record of incarceration using jail records received from the Broward County Sheriffs Office from January 2013 to April 2016. These were supplemented with public incarceration records that were downloaded from the Florida Department of Corrections website. Altogether, there were 2,809 defendants who recidivated within two years in this sample (ibid.).

Section 1. Exploratory Data Analysis

(a) Filter out missing data from regular recidivism data

The original data set contained 7214 records. Following the ProPublica methodology, any row determined not to be useable for the first round of analysis were removed. The reasons cited for removing rows are explained as follows:

-If the charge date of a defendants COMPAS scored crime was not within 30 days from when the person was arrested, we assume that because of data quality reasons, that we do not have the right offense. -We coded the recidivist flag is_recid to be -1 if we could not find a compas case at all. -In a similar vein, ordinary traffic offenses those with a c_charge_degree of O will not result in Jail time are removed (only two of them). -We filtered the underlying data from Broward county to include only those rows representing people who had either recidivated in two years, or had at least two years outside of a correctional facility (https://github.com/propublica/compas-analysis/blob/master/Compas%20Analysis.ipynb).

After filtering the data, we are left with 6172 records.

The rates of recidivism in the sample population varies by age category, race, sex. When we look specifically at race, we find that black defendents have the highest recidivism rates at 51.44%, followed by white defendents with 34.07%, and Hispanic defendents at 8.25%. All other racial categories have recidivism rates less than 1%.

When we look at age, we find that recidivism rates within the 25-45 age category are 36.28 percentage points higher than the greater than 45 age group and 35.4 percentage points greater than the under 25 age group.

Finally, when we look at sex, we find that men had recidivism rates 61.92 percentage points higher than women.

These facts together suggest that we should find the highest recidivism rates among black men between the ages of 25 and 45. We can test this hypothesis by further breaking down the statistics by additional attributes, as Ive done in the composite tables above. Referring to these tables, we see that, indeed, this hypothesis bears out. In fact this category of defendents has recidivism rates 11.37 percentage points higher than the next highest group, white men between the ages of 25 and 45.

A point to note, however, is that the sample sizes vary significantly between each of these categories of defendents, meaning that we should expect higher margins of error in our estimates for those groups with smaller sample sizes.

# Create panel.cor function
panel.cor <- function(x, y, digits = 2, prefix = "", cex.cor, ...)
{
    usr <- par("usr"); on.exit(par(usr))
    par(usr = c(0, 1, 0, 1))
    r <- abs(cor(x, y))
    txt <- format(c(r, 0.123456789), digits = digits)[1]
    txt <- paste0(prefix, txt)
    if(missing(cex.cor)) cex.cor <- 0.8/strwidth(txt)
    text(0.5, 0.5, txt, cex = pmax(1, cex.cor * r))
}

# Use panel.cor to display correlations in lower panel
pairs(raw_data1[,quant.vars1], lower.panel = panel.cor)

The correlation matrix above only shows strong correlation between the is_recid and two_year_recid predictors, which wed expect since the one variable is used to calculate the other. Nonetheless, this observation reminds us why it might not be a good idea to include them both as predictors as including them both may tend to exaggerate the influence either one of them is exerting on the outcome, or otherwise mask their individual effect in that relationship. In our primary model, of course, two_year_recid is serving as our outcome variable, so the bigger concern would be using is_recid as a predictor in this model. Most of these observations are obvious once you give them a seconds thought, so Overall, the matrix above is not particulary informative. The histograms above show that the highest two-year recidism scores are assigned to black male defendents between the ages of 25 and 45, which is consistent with what wed expect given the higher base rates of recidivism among this group. While white defendents are also given relatively high scores by the COMPAS RAI, the distribution of scores is much more skewed toward the low end of the score range compared to black defendents, where the distribution is much more uniform. In other words, white defendents are much more likely to receive low risk evaluations by the COMPAS system than are black defendents. Note: A decile score of 1-4 is low (below average), 5-7 is moderate (average), and 8-10 is high (above average) (http://www.northpointeinc.com/files/technical_documents/FieldGuide2_081412.pdf).

Next, I fit a logistic regression model to the regular recidivism data using the two-year recidivism rates as the response and age and the count of prior offenses as the inputs. Two_year_recid is a binary variable. As such, the model below should be intepreted as providing an estimate of the probability of a defendent revidivating as the defendents age and number of prior offenses varies. These probability estimates can then be used to classify particular defendents as recidivators or non-recidivators according to various thresholds we might set. For the purposes of this exercise, a cutoff of .5 is used to classify a score as either Low or High, which is turn is used to predict the defendent who earns that score as either a recidivator or non-recidivator.

The ProPublica team used logistic regression to test whether there was a significant difference in COMPAS scores between races. In order to do this, they first had to change some variables into factors, and run a logistic regression comparing low scores to high scores. We dont need to repeat their work here, but its worth noting that that exercise showed that, indeed, there was a significant difference in COMPAS scores between races. Specfically, they found that black defendents were 45% more likely than white defendants to receive a higher score after correcting for the seriousness of their crime, previous arrests, and future criminal behavior. Perhaps more surprisingly, the COMPAS system was also substantially more likely to give high scores to female defendents (19.4% more likely, to be exact) than to male defendents and 250% more likely to give high scores to defendents under the age of 25 than to middle-aged defendents (https://github.com/propublica/compas-analysis/blob/master/Compas%20Analysis.ipynb).

In the first model, both age and priors_count are statistically significant at the p < 0.05 level. In the second model, the statistically significant predictors are (Intercept), age_catGreater than 45, age_catLess than 25, priors_count, sexMale, raceHispanic, raceOther.

The coefficients derived from the logistic regression model indicate the change in the expected log odds relative to a one unit change in each predictor, X1, holding all other predictors constant (see http://sphweb.bumc.bu.edu/otlt/MPH-Modules/BS/BS704_Multivariable/BS704_Multivariable8.html). The intercept, in the case of the second model, represents a hypothetical black female defendent between the ages of 25 and 45. Relative to this baseline, being male increases the expected log odds of recidivating by 35.7 percentage points holding all other predictors constant. In contrast, being Hispanic reduces the expected log odds of recidivating by 28.2 percentage points holding all other predictors constant. Similarly, being in the greater than 45 age group reduces the expected log odds of recidivating by a surprising 67.8 percentage points holding all other predictors constant. Finally, having one additional prior offense on your record increases the expected log odds of recidivating by 17 percentage points holding all other predictors constant.

(g) Calculate decile scores for your logistic regression model

[Incomplete]

The COMPAS scale scores are transformed into deciles, which were obtained by ranking the scale scores of a normative group in ascending order and then dividing these scores into ten equal sized groups (http://www.northpointeinc.com/files/technical_documents/FieldGuide2_081412.pdf). I follow a similar method here to ensure that any evaluations I perform of my models preditive accuracy are comparable to those of the COMPAS tool. If I were to use a different scaling system, I would not be able to determine definitively if any difference in accuracy between the two models was due to these differences in scale (i.e., were merely an artifact of the different methodology employed) or due to superior predicive ability for the target population (which is what were truly interested in).

First, raw risk scores were calculated for each of the defendents in the sample population using the ___ RAI, which was determined above to have the highest RUC curve value. Next, I used the quantiles function to separate the defendents into ten equal sized bins. The cutoff values for the ten quantiles were used to tranform risk scores into deciles. Finally, I used a confusion matrix to calculate the predictive accuracy of my model, which I then compared with the accuracy of the COMPAS RAI.

Section 2. Methodology

My general approach in executing this project was to follow method outlined here by the ProPublica team: https://github.com/propublica/compas-analysis/blob/master/Compas%20Analysis.ipynb. I adapted their methodology to better suit the parameters of this project, resulting in the following list of actions:

(Due to time restrictions, I was unable to complete all of the steps included in the plan below. I include them here to indicate what my strategy would have been had I more time to complete the project, or to otherwise indicate my level of understanding of the process as of the moment this assignment was submitted.)

  1. Do descriptive analysis of violent recidivism outcomes and inputs
  2. Fit a logistic regression model with just two variables (to make sure model works)
  3. Add additional variables to your regression model
  4. Fit a lasso to your expanded regression model and identify best subset of variables
  5. Revise regression model according to results of lasso
  6. Fit a random forest model with just two variables (to make sure model works)

  11. Calculate decile scores for each of your models
  12. Evaluate performance of two models and compare; determine which is superior
  13. Compare the performance of your chosen model (using the calculated decile scores) with that of the COMPAS RAI.
  14. Use logistic regression to check for bias in your models, just like the ProPublica team did in section (e).
  15. Draw conclusions and discuss.
(a) Overview and Evaluation of Data Mining Methods Used

Descriptive Methods In conducting this analysis, I used the following data mining methods. First, I ran descriptive statistics on the raw data for both general recidivism as well as violent recidivism to see how the outcome of interest (two_year_recid) is associated with different values of the race, sex, and age of the individual. I used simple summary tables to obtain a breakdown of recisivism scores by age_cat, sex, race, and priors_count. Next, I evaluated the performance of the COMPAS RAI by analyzing its assignment of decile scores by race, sex, and age_category. Finally, I ran tests for colinearity (specifically, the pairs function) in order to identify redunandant variables that might be masking the effects of the predictors of interest.

Predictive Methods Second, I fit a logistic regression model to the relationship between the outcome and several variables I expected to be most strongly associated with the outcome, namely, race, sex, age category, and number of prior offenses. After building the model, I examined the summary table to determine which predictors were statistically significant at the p < .05 level. I used the results of this tests to eliminate any variable that was redundant or not statistically significant from my final model (i.e., my Broward County-specific RAI).

Next, I used the BIC method to select the best model. I chose to use the BIC method rather than the AIC method because I preferred a simpler model. Simple models have more bias than more complex models, but less variability, meaning they tend to have less error when applied to the test data set.

Third, I fit a random forest model to the relationship between the outcome and the same variables I used in my first model (logistic regression). I did this to see if one model did a significantly better job at modeling the relationship.

In both the logistic and random forest models, I began by building the simplest version of the respective models to ensure that the they were functional before attempting to add additional variables. I did this as a means of troubleshooting each model before it became too complex to be able to quickly diagnose the cause of any subsequent malfunction. Once I had each model functioning properly, I proceeded to add variables one by one until I had I had included all the variables I judged to be most significant. In the case of the logistic regression model, I then used the lasso method to select the best subset of variables from those that I had included. The resulting model became my final model for this exercise.

Fourth, I compared the performance of the two final models (the logistic regression and random forest models) by calculating the cross validation error. I used confusion matrices to display the proportion of accurate to erroneous predictions relative to the actual recidivism rates. I did this for both regular as well as violent recidivism.

Fifth, I generated decile scores for my final model by calculating what proportion of defendents in the sample fell within each bin (get each score). Next, I created proportions tables to display these proportions and identified cut points to model probabilities (specifically, I used 9 cut points in order to produce 10 bins of equal size to the COMPAS proportions). For these steps, I used the CUMSUM, quantile, and prop table functions.

Lastly, I graphed the ROC curve for my final model alongside the ROC curve for the COMPAS RAI and compared their relative AUC values. In my assessment of the AUC, I used a threshold of .67 to evaluate whether my risk assessment was performing adequately.

The predictors in the first (logistic regression) model whose coefficient estimates are statistically significant at the p < 0.05 level are (Intercept), age_catGreater than 45, age_catLess than 25, priors_count, sexMale, raceHispanic, raceOther. The coefficients derived from the logistic regression model indicate the change in the expected log odds relative to a one unit change in each predictor, X1, holding all other predictors constant (see http://sphweb.bumc.bu.edu/otlt/MPH-Modules/BS/BS704_Multivariable/BS704_Multivariable8.html). The intercept represents a hypothetical black female defendent between the ages of 25 and 45. Relative to this baseline, being male increases the expected log odds of recidivating by 35.7 percentage points holding all other predictors constant. In contrast, being Hispanic reduces the expected log odds of recidivating by 28.2 percentage points holding all other predictors constant. Similarly, being in the greater than 45 age group reduces the expected log odds of recidivating by a surprising 67.8 percentage points holding all other predictors constant. Finally, having one additional prior offense on your record increases the expected log odds of recidivating by 17 percentage points holding all other predictors constant.

# Evaluate performance of your RAI

ProPublicas assessment of the COMPAS RAI found that black defendants were far more likely than white defendants to be incorrectly judged to be at a higher risk of recidivism, while white defendants were more likely than black defendants to be incorrectly flagged as low risk (https://www.propublica.org/article/how-we-analyzed-the-compas-recidivism-algorithm).

The ProPublica team compared the recidivism risk scores predicted by the COMPAS tool to the actual recidivism rates of defendants in the two years after they were scored and found that the score correctly predicted an offenders recidivism 61 percent of the time, but was only correct in its predictions of violent recidivism 20 percent of the time (ibid.).

In forecasting who would re-offend, the algorithm correctly predicted recidivism for black and white defendants at roughly the same rate (59 percent for white defendants, and 63 percent for black defendants) but made mistakes in very different ways. It misclassifies the white and black defendants differently when examined over a two-year follow-up period.
